<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="45" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="45">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="45">
<bibRefCitation author="Griffini, A" journalOrPublisher="Memoires de la Societe entomologique Belgique" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" pagination="201 - 226" refId="B6" refString="Griffini, A, 1908. Phasgonuridae africane del R. Museo di Storia Naturale in Bruxelles. 6. Phaneropteridae pars 2a (reliquae species omnes). Memoires de la Societe entomologique Belgique 15: 201 - 226" title="Phasgonuridae africane del R. Museo di Storia Naturale in Bruxelles. 6. Phaneropteridae pars 2 a (reliquae species omnes)." volume="15" year="1908">Griffini (1908)</bibRefCitation>
supposed that, because 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Bolívar">Bolivar</normalizedToken>
(1906) overlooked the paper of 
<bibRefCitation author="Sjoestedt, Y" journalOrPublisher="Bihang till Kungliga Svenska Vetenskaps-Akademiens Handlingar" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" pagination="1 - 45" refId="B40" refString="Sjoestedt, Y, 1902. Locustodeen aus Kamerun und Kongo. Bihang till Kungliga Svenska Vetenskaps-Akademiens Handlingar 27 (3): 1 - 45" title="Locustodeen aus Kamerun und Kongo." volume="27" year="1902">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Sjöstedt">Sjoestedt</normalizedToken>
(1902)
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. gladiator" order="Orthoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gladiator">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">P. gladiator</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken originalValue="Bolívar">Bolivar</normalizedToken>
, 1906 from Cameroon could be synonymous with 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. forcipata" order="Orthoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="forcipata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">P. forcipata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken originalValue="Sjöstedt">Sjoestedt</normalizedToken>
, 1902, also from Cameroon. The male cerci of the two taxa are identical. Both lack the black marking on the stridulatory area of the male left tegmen (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 52–56" captionStartId="F10" captionText="Figures 52 - 56. Morphological details of male P. gladiator (= P. forcipata) (lectotypus). Habitus (52), stridulatory file on the underside of left tegminal flap (53), stridulatory area (54), dorsal view (55) and ventral view (56) on apex. Arrow in Fig. 55 shows the asymmetrical spine." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.68.60193.figures52-56" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/499189" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">54</figureCitation>
); thus 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. gladiator" order="Orthoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gladiator">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">P. gladiator</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been synonymised with 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. forcipata" order="Orthoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="forcipata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">P. forcipata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1665/034.022.0201" author="Massa, B" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Orthoptera Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" pagination="125 - 152" refId="B24" refString="Massa, B, 2013. Diversity of leaf katydids (Orthoptera: Tettigoniidae: Phaneropterinae) of Dzanga-Ndoki National Park, Central African Republic, with selected records from other African countries. Journal of Orthoptera Research 22 (2): 125 - 152, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1665/034.022.0201" title="Diversity of leaf katydids (Orthoptera: Tettigoniidae: Phaneropterinae) of Dzanga-Ndoki National Park, Central African Republic, with selected records from other African countries." url="https://doi.org/10.1665/034.022.0201" volume="22" year="2013">Massa (2013)</bibRefCitation>
. Morphologically most closely related to 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. laeglae" order="Orthoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laeglae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">P. laeglae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(both species share an asymmetrical supra-anal plate with a spine on the left margin, Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 52–56" captionStartId="F10" captionText="Figures 52 - 56. Morphological details of male P. gladiator (= P. forcipata) (lectotypus). Habitus (52), stridulatory file on the underside of left tegminal flap (53), stridulatory area (54), dorsal view (55) and ventral view (56) on apex. Arrow in Fig. 55 shows the asymmetrical spine." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.68.60193.figures52-56" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/499189" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">55</figureCitation>
), 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. tshuapa" order="Orthoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tshuapa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">P. tshuapa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. and 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. magnicerca" order="Orthoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="magnicerca">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">P. magnicerca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(also see diagnosis at 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. laeglae" order="Orthoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laeglae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">P. laeglae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="45" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="45">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="45">
Rather stout species with comparatively broad tegmina (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 52–56" captionStartId="F10" captionText="Figures 52 - 56. Morphological details of male P. gladiator (= P. forcipata) (lectotypus). Habitus (52), stridulatory file on the underside of left tegminal flap (53), stridulatory area (54), dorsal view (55) and ventral view (56) on apex. Arrow in Fig. 55 shows the asymmetrical spine." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.68.60193.figures52-56" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/499189" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">54</figureCitation>
). The 10th abdominal tergite is broad with two lateral processes, while the cerci are highly modified into two branches (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 52–56" captionStartId="F10" captionText="Figures 52 - 56. Morphological details of male P. gladiator (= P. forcipata) (lectotypus). Habitus (52), stridulatory file on the underside of left tegminal flap (53), stridulatory area (54), dorsal view (55) and ventral view (56) on apex. Arrow in Fig. 55 shows the asymmetrical spine." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.68.60193.figures52-56" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/499189" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">55</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 52–56" captionStartId="F10" captionText="Figures 52 - 56. Morphological details of male P. gladiator (= P. forcipata) (lectotypus). Habitus (52), stridulatory file on the underside of left tegminal flap (53), stridulatory area (54), dorsal view (55) and ventral view (56) on apex. Arrow in Fig. 55 shows the asymmetrical spine." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.68.60193.figures52-56" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/499189" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">56</figureCitation>
). The inner branch is blade-like with sclerotised margins, while the outer or apical one is finger-like (also see at 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. tshuapa" order="Orthoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tshuapa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">P. tshuapa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov.). This species has an asymmetrical supra-anal plate with a stout spine on the left side, lacking on the right (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4780.3.1" author="Massa, B" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" pagination="401 - 447" refId="B31" refString="Massa, B, Annoyer, P, Perez, C, Danflous, S, Duvot, G, 2020. Orthoptera Tettigoniidae (Conocephalinae, Hexacentrinae, Phaneropterinae, Mecopodinae, Hetrodinae) from some protected areas of Central African Republic. Zootaxa 4780 (3): 401 - 447, DOI: https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4780.3.1" title="Orthoptera Tettigoniidae (Conocephalinae, Hexacentrinae, Phaneropterinae, Mecopodinae, Hetrodinae) from some protected areas of Central African Republic." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4780.3.1" volume="4780" year="2020">Massa et al. 2020</bibRefCitation>
; Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 52–56" captionStartId="F10" captionText="Figures 52 - 56. Morphological details of male P. gladiator (= P. forcipata) (lectotypus). Habitus (52), stridulatory file on the underside of left tegminal flap (53), stridulatory area (54), dorsal view (55) and ventral view (56) on apex. Arrow in Fig. 55 shows the asymmetrical spine." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.68.60193.figures52-56" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/499189" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">55</figureCitation>
arrow). The male subgenital plate is triangular and has a small apical concavity (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 52–56" captionStartId="F10" captionText="Figures 52 - 56. Morphological details of male P. gladiator (= P. forcipata) (lectotypus). Habitus (52), stridulatory file on the underside of left tegminal flap (53), stridulatory area (54), dorsal view (55) and ventral view (56) on apex. Arrow in Fig. 55 shows the asymmetrical spine." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.68.60193.figures52-56" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/499189" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">56</figureCitation>
). The stridulatory file has ca. 35 teeth, the last 8-10 placed more or less perpendicularly to the main file (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 52–56" captionStartId="F10" captionText="Figures 52 - 56. Morphological details of male P. gladiator (= P. forcipata) (lectotypus). Habitus (52), stridulatory file on the underside of left tegminal flap (53), stridulatory area (54), dorsal view (55) and ventral view (56) on apex. Arrow in Fig. 55 shows the asymmetrical spine." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.68.60193.figures52-56" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/499189" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">53</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
